<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"asinh"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"=
acosh"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"atanh"></span><span class=3D"anc=
hor" id=3D"asech"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"acsch"></span><span c=
lass=3D"anchor" id=3D"acoth"></span>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Graphs_of_the_inverse_hyperbolic_functions.pn=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/w=
ikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Graphs_of_the_inverse_hyperbolic_functions.png/=
330px-Graphs_of_the_inverse_hyperbolic_functions.png" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"310" height=3D"231" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"169=
4" data-file-height=3D"1262"></a><figcaption>Graphs of the inverse hyperbol=
ic functions</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hyperbolic_functions_sinh,_co=
sh,_tanh.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wiki=
media.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Hyperbolic_functions_sinh%2C_cosh%2C=
_tanh.png/330px-Hyperbolic_functions_sinh%2C_cosh%2C_tanh.png" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"310" height=3D"244" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"1466" data-file-height=3D"1156"></a><figcaption>The hyperbolic functi=
ons <span class=3D"texhtml">sinh</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">cosh</span=
>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">tanh</span> with respect to a unit hyperbola=
 are analogous to circular functions <span class=3D"texhtml">sin</span>, <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">cos</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">tan</span> with r=
espect to a unit circle. The argument to the hyperbolic functions is a hype=
rbolic angle measure.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>inverse hyperbolic functions</b> are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_function" title=3D"Inverse functi=
on">inverses</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic=
_functions" title=3D"Hyperbolic functions">hyperbolic functions</a>, analog=
ous to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_trigonometric_f=
unctions" title=3D"Inverse trigonometric functions">inverse circular functi=
ons</a>. There are six in common use: inverse hyperbolic sine, inverse hype=
rbolic cosine, inverse hyperbolic tangent, inverse hyperbolic cosecant, inv=
erse hyperbolic secant, and inverse hyperbolic cotangent. They are commonly=
 denoted by the symbols for the hyperbolic functions, prefixed with <i>arc-=
</i> or <i>ar-</i> or with a superscript <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mw=
e-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathm=
l-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math=
/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {-1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {-1}}</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/76a7a8e06f9f953ac8acb92698ce7ff6fa523bd7" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:2.971ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {-1=
}}"></span> (for example <span class=3D"texhtml">arcsinh</span>, <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">arsinh</span>, or <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-el=
ement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" s=
tyle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" =
alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \sinh ^{-1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>sinh</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sinh ^{-1}}<=
/annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5009e90dbc0b87a37bb73b90627180776dbc6fe6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:6.481ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \si=
nh ^{-1}}"></span>).
</p><p>For a given value of a hyperbolic function, the inverse hyperbolic f=
unction provides the corresponding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Hyperbolic_angle" title=3D"Hyperbolic angle">hyperbolic angle measure</a>,=
 for example <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: no=
ne;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displa=
ystyle \operatorname {arsinh} (\sinh a)=3Da}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>arsinh</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>sinh</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \operatorname=
 {arsinh} (\sinh a)=3Da}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9945b886132649d8b62be19c2a931f3e0f6394de" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:18.125ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \o=
peratorname {arsinh} (\sinh a)=3Da}"></span> and <span class=3D"mwe-math-el=
ement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-ma=
th-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1=
998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \sinh(\operatorname {arsinh} x)=
=3Dx.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>sinh</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>arsinh</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sinh(\operat=
orname {arsinh} x)=3Dx.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0660894b238168fc9acc074376ac0595b7b26fa8" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:18.971ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \s=
inh(\operatorname {arsinh} x)=3Dx.}"></span> Hyperbolic angle measure is th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_length" title=3D"Arc length"=
>length of an arc</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_hy=
perbola" title=3D"Unit hyperbola">unit hyperbola</a> <span class=3D"mwe-mat=
h-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mw=
e-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x^{2}-y^{2}=3D1}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>y</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x^{2}-y^{2}=
=3D1}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/66b6dc015284f725f6537eb50fe4b20348cf0a5a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:11.7ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x^{2=
}-y^{2}=3D1}"></span> as measured in the Lorentzian plane (<em>not</em> the=
 length of a hyperbolic arc in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Euclidean_plane" title=3D"Euclidean plane">Euclidean plane</a>), and twice=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a>=
 of the corresponding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_s=
ector" title=3D"Hyperbolic sector">hyperbolic sector</a>. This is analogous=
 to the way <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle"=
>circular angle measure</a> is the arc length of an arc of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_circle" title=3D"Unit circle">unit circle=
</a> in the Euclidean plane or twice the area of the corresponding <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_sector" title=3D"Circular sector=
">circular sector</a>. Alternately hyperbolic angle is the area of a sector=
 of the hyperbola <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle xy=3D1.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle xy=3D1.}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/65451c8a210ae9635d8e1cfb592b8e3be0084a50" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:7.393ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle xy=
=3D1.}"></span> Some authors call the inverse hyperbolic functions <i>hyper=
bolic area functions</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-1"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>Hyperbolic functions occur in the calculation of angles and distance=
s in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D=
"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic geometry</a>. They also occur in the solut=
ions of many linear <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_e=
quation" title=3D"Differential equation">differential equations</a> (such a=
s the equation defining a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catenary=
" title=3D"Catenary">catenary</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cubic_function#Hyperbolic_solution_for_one_real_root" title=3D"Cubic func=
tion">cubic equations</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lap=
lace%27s_equation" title=3D"Laplace's equation">Laplace's equation</a> in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinates" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Cartesian coordinates">Cartesian coordinates</a>. <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace%27s_equation" title=3D"Laplace's=
 equation">Laplace's equations</a> are important in many areas of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>, i=
ncluding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_theory" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electromagnetic theory">electromagnetic theor=
y</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_transfer" title=3D"Hea=
t transfer">heat transfer</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flu=
id_dynamics" title=3D"Fluid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>, and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Special relativity=
">special relativity</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Notation">Notation</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInverse_hyperbolic_f=
unctions&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Notation=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hyperbolic_functions-2.svg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/b/bc/Hyperbolic_functions-2.svg/330px-Hyperbolic_functions-2.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"262" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=3D"437"></a><figcaption>A ray through=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_hyperbola" title=3D"Unit=
 hyperbola">unit hyperbola</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup>=
 =E2=88=92 <i>y</i><sup>2</sup> =3D 1</span> in the point <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">(cosh <i>a</i>, sinh <i>a</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> is twice the area between the r=
ay, the hyperbola, and the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">x</span>-axis</figcaption></figure>
<p>The earliest and most widely adopted symbols use the prefix <i>arc-</i> =
(that is: <span class=3D"texhtml">arcsinh</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">a=
rccosh</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">arctanh</span>, <span class=3D"texht=
ml">arcsech</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">arccsch</span>, <span class=3D"=
texhtml">arccoth</span>), by analogy with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Inverse_trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Inverse trigonometric=
 functions">inverse circular functions</a> (<span class=3D"texhtml">arcsin<=
/span>, etc.). For a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_hyperbol=
a" title=3D"Unit hyperbola">unit hyperbola</a> ("Lorentzian circle") in the=
 Lorentzian plane (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-Euclidea=
n_space" title=3D"Pseudo-Euclidean space">pseudo-Euclidean plane</a> of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_signature" title=3D"Metric sig=
nature">signature</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">(1, 1)</span>)<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invers=
e_hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hy=
perbolic number">hyperbolic number</a> plane,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_hyperbolic_=
functions#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hyperbolic_angle" title=3D"Hyperbolic angle">hyperbolic angle measure</=
a> (argument to the hyperbolic functions) is indeed the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_length" title=3D"Arc length">arc length</a> of a =
hyperbolic arc.
</p><p>Also common is the notation <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math=
-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y=
" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM=
L" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \sinh ^{-1},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>sinh</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
